    <div class="educational-section">
      <div class="edu-header">
        <h2>The Complete Guide to Fuel Efficiency</h2>
        <p>Understanding the science and economics behind your miles per gallon.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="edu-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3><span class="edu-card-icon">📊</span> The Math Behind MPG</h3>
          <p>Miles Per Gallon (MPG) is the standard measure of fuel efficiency in the United States. To calculate cost manually:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Formula:</strong> (Distance ÷ MPG) × Price per Gallon</li>
            <li><strong>Example:</strong> If you drive 300 miles in a car that gets 30 MPG, you'll use 10 gallons of gas. At $3.50 per gallon, the trip costs exactly $35.00.</li>
            <li><strong>Diminishing Returns:</strong> Upgrading from 10 MPG to 20 MPG saves a massive 50 gallons over 1000 miles. But upgrading from 40 MPG to 50 MPG only saves 5 gallons over the same distance. The lower your current MPG, the more a small upgrade saves!</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3><span class="edu-card-icon">🏎️</span> Real-World vs EPA MPG</h3>
          <p>The EPA MPG on your window sticker is tested under highly controlled laboratory conditions. In the real world, you rarely hit those exact numbers:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Speeding:</strong> Gas mileage usually decreases rapidly at speeds above 50 mph. Every 5 mph you drive over 50 mph is like paying an extra $0.25 per gallon.</li>
            <li><strong>Weather:</strong> Cold weather increases aerodynamic drag, increases oil viscosity, and takes longer to warm up the engine, severely impacting short-trip MPG.</li>
            <li><strong>AC Usage:</strong> Running the air conditioning in hot weather can reduce fuel economy by more than 25% on a conventional vehicle.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3><span class="edu-card-icon">💰</span> Actionable Ways to Save Gas</h3>
          <p>You don't need a new car to save money at the pump. Simple habit changes make a big difference:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Tire Pressure:</strong> Keeping tires properly inflated can improve your gas mileage by up to 3%. Under-inflated tires increase rolling resistance.</li>
            <li><strong>Shed Weight:</strong> Avoid keeping unnecessary items in your vehicle. An extra 100 pounds in your vehicle could reduce your MPG by up to 1%.</li>
            <li><strong>Smooth Driving:</strong> Aggressive driving (speeding, rapid acceleration, and braking) wastes gas. It can lower your gas mileage by 15% to 30% at highway speeds and 10% to 40% in stop-and-go traffic.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3><span class="edu-card-icon">⚡</span> The EV Equivalent (MPGe)</h3>
          <p>Electric vehicles don't use liquid fuel, so the EPA created MPGe (Miles Per Gallon Equivalent) to compare efficiency to gas cars.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>The Baseline:</strong> One gallon of gasoline contains the energy equivalent of 33.7 kilowatt-hours (kWh) of electricity.</li>
            <li><strong>The Calculation:</strong> An EV rated at 100 MPGe uses 33.7 kWh to travel 100 miles.</li>
            <li><strong>Cost Difference:</strong> While a gallon of gas might cost $3.50, the equivalent 33.7 kWh of electricity usually costs around $4.70 to $5.40 at home, but takes you 3-4 times further because electric motors are immensely more efficient than combustion engines.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <div class="faq-header">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Common questions about calculating gas costs and road trip planning.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do you calculate gas cost for a trip?</h3>
          <p>To calculate the gas cost for a trip, divide the total distance (in miles) by your vehicle's fuel efficiency (MPG), then multiply that number by the price of gas per gallon. For example, a 100-mile trip at 25 MPG and $3.50/gallon costs (100 / 25) * 3.50 = $14.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many gallons of gas do I need for a 500 mile trip?</h3>
          <p>The gallons needed for a 500-mile trip depend entirely on your car's MPG. If your car gets 20 MPG, you need 25 gallons (500/20). At 30 MPG, you need about 16.7 gallons. At 40 MPG, you only need 12.5 gallons.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much does a 30-minute commute cost in gas?</h3>
          <p>A 30-minute commute typically covers 15-25 miles. In a 25 MPG car at $3.50 per gallon, a 20-mile commute costs $2.80 each way, or $5.60 per day. Over a 5-day work week, that's $28, or about $1,400 per year.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is it cheaper to fly or drive?</h3>
          <p>For solo travelers, flying is often cheaper for distances over 500 miles. However, for families or groups of 3+, driving is usually significantly cheaper because you split the vehicle's gas cost, whereas airline tickets are priced per person. You must also factor in the cost of a rental car at your destination vs driving your own car, as well as lodging and food for multi-day road trips.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How accurate are online gas calculators?</h3>
          <p>Online gas calculators are highly accurate mathematically based on the numbers you input. However, real-world MPG often differs from EPA estimates. Factors like driving habits (speeding, rapid acceleration), AC usage, tire pressure, elevation changes, and cargo weight can lower your actual MPG by 10-20% compared to ideal estimates. For the most accurate calculation, track your own actual MPG by resetting your trip odometer when you fill up, and dividing those miles by the gallons added at your next fill-up.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

